						<div class="comment green">
							<div class="comment-body">
								<p>I just finished making six cups of the ricotta for a double batch of lasagna. I tried three different kinds of milk from the same supplier (Dairyland in BC, Canada); I used organic whole milk, and their standard whole milk in both plastic jugs and waxed paper cartons.</p>

<p>The results:</p>

<p>I'm guessing that the organic was not UHT since it made beautiful ricotta. One type of milk gave a much lower yield than the others -- it was the whole milk in the waxed paper carton. The curds never came together and the yield per session was about half compared to the milk stored in plastic jugs. Each time and for each type of milk, I did 8 cups of milk, 8 Tbsp of white vinegar and a scant Tbsp of kosher salt in the microwave until it reached 165.</p>

<p>I'd be interested to hear if anyone else can reproduce these results. I'll stick to milk in plastic jugs from now on for this application.</p>
								<div class="comment-body-bottom"></div>
							</div>
							<p class="commenter postFooter"><a href="http://www.seriouseats.com/user/profile/TheHoff">TheHoff</a> at <a href="http://www.seriouseats.com/2010/02/how-to-make-fresh-ricotta-fast-easy-homemade-cheese-the-food-lab.html#611472"> 4:16PM on 11/28/10</a></p>
						</div><!-- close comment -->
					

				</div><!-- end comments -->
				
				

<a name="ihascommented"></a><div id="commented" style="display: none;"><p>Thanks for commenting!<br />Your comment has been accepted<br />and will appear in a moment.</p></div>

